## 6. Execution Order

```
Phase 0:  Fix local_reranker.py (1 line, deploy immediately, low risk)
Phase 1:  Rebuild Kaggle notebook → generate new chunks_XXXX.sqlite files
Phase 2:  python push_sqlite_to_qdrant.py --reset
          python enrich_qdrant_metadata.py --write
Phase 3:  Apply retriever.py changes (2 surgical edits)
Phase 4:  Smoke test: send 5 representative legal queries, verify child_text
          appears in logs and parent_text is sent to the LLM
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Do Phase 0 first — it can be deployed independently and immediately removes the silent truncation bug from your current system even before the data rebuild.

---

## 7. Trade-off Summary

| What You Gain | What You Pay |
|---|---|
| Higher ANN candidate recall for specific legal queries (+8–20%) | One-time data pipeline rebuild (hours) |
| Reranker reads correct text, not truncated prefix | ~1–2 GB additional disk space in Qdrant volume |
| LLM receives logically complete legal articles | Minor increase in child point count (~6x, within RAM budget) |
| Citation IDs remain stable (`parent_id = cid`) | 5 files touched, but all changes are 1–5 line surgical edits |
| COMPARE/MULTI_HOP accuracy improves significantly | prefetch limit must be tuned (top_k × 4 instead of top_k × 2) |

**Bottom line:** This is the right architecture for legal RAG with structured documents under constrained infrastructure. The benefits compound across all 7 query intents and the change set is minimally invasive.
